-- BHP, Gunns, Healthscope, Newcrest, Nufarm, Linc, Santos: Equity Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-14T22:09:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-14/bhp-gunns-healthscope-newcrest-nufarm-linc-santos-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed yesterday. All
prices are from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in September
declined 0.4 percent to 4,429 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The
 Bank of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 0.1 percent. The
 S&P/ASX 200 Index  increased 1.9 percent to 4,462.40.  
 Mining shares: A measure of metals traded in London rose
0.4 percent.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
increased 2.1 percent to A$38.40 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts slipped 0.1 percent in New York trading.  
 Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining
company, decreased 1.3 percent to A$67.38 in Sydney.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil for August delivery was little
changed to settle at $77.04 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, advanced 1.6 percent to A$43.
Rival  Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) rose 0.6 percent to A$13.90.  
 Gold producers: Gold futures for August delivery fell 0.5
percent to $1,207 an ounce in New York.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, rose 1.3 percent to A$35.27.  
 Gunns Ltd  (GNS AU): Australia’s biggest woodchip exporter
was downgraded to “neutral” from “buy” at UBS AG by equity
analyst  Lachlan Parker . Gunns increased 3.2 percent to 65.5
Australian cents.  
 Linc Energy Ltd.  (LNC AU): Australia-based Linc, which
converts coal into liquid fuels, said it’s in “advanced” talks
with three buyers, including India’s Adani Enterprises Ltd., to
sell coking coal assets in Australia. Adani is in talks to buy
the Galilee tenement, or permit, valued at more than A$1 billion
($884 million), Chief Executive Officer  Peter Bond  said by phone.
Linc surged 31 percent A$1.38.  
 Healthscope Ltd.  (HSP AU): The Carlyle Group may exit the
TPG-led bidding group for Healthscope due to disagreement over
pricing, the Australian Financial Review reported in its Street
Talk column, without saying where it got the information. The
consortium, which includes TPG, Blackstone Group LP and Carlyle
Group, is competing with Kohlberg Kravis & Roberts for
Australia’s second-largest hospital operator, with final bids
due tomorrow, the newspaper said. Healthscope gained 1.7 percent
to A$5.46.  
 Nufarm Ltd.  (NUF AU): Australia’s largest supplier of farm
chemicals cut its full-year profit forecast because of
unfavorable weather in North America, Europe and parts of
Australia. Net operating profit is forecast at A$55 million ($48
million) to A$65 million for the 12 months ending July 31, the
Melbourne-based company said in a statement. That compared with
its March forecast of A$110 million to A$130 million. Nufarm
dropped 2.1 percent to A$5.24.  
